[[File:MaryPickfordPortrait.jpg|thumb|[[Mary Pickford]] wearing a boudoir cap and negligee in 1921]]
A '''boudoir cap''' is a form of [[lingerie]] hat that was popularly worn in the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries.<ref>{{cite book|last=Cumming|first=Valerie|title=The dictionary of fashion history |date=2010 |publisher=Berg |location=Oxford |isbn=9781847887382 |pages=55–56 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=glBf_El4Qd4C&pg=PT56#v=onepage&q&f=false |author2=Cunnington, C.W. |author3=Cunnington, P.E.}}</ref> In its original form, the boudoir cap was worn over undressed hair,<ref>{{cite book|last=Lewandowski|first=Elizabeth J.|title=The complete costume dictionary|date=2011|publisher=Scarecrow Press, Inc.|location=Lanham, Md.|isbn=9780810877856|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gbIsJ2tZJS4C&pg=PA36#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> and has been compared to the 18th century [[mob cap]].<ref name=chico/><ref>{{cite web|title=Boudoir cap, ca. 1917, American.|url=http://metmuseum.org/collections/search-the-collections/157739|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|accessdate=7 May 2014}}</ref>  Particularly towards the end it was designed to be worn in the privacy of the [[boudoir]] with [[negligee]]s or [[nightwear]].<ref name=chico>{{cite book |last=Chico |first=Beverly |title=Hats and headwear around the world : a cultural encyclopedia |date=2013 |publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, Calif. |isbn=9781610690638 |pages=295–296 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GdbYAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA295#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> It was often made from lightweight lingerie-type fabrics such as [[muslin]] or [[net (textile)|net]] and trimmed with silk ribbon and lace.<ref name=chico/> During its later revival in the 1910s and 1920s, it was used to protect short hairstyles whilst sleeping,<ref name=cunnington>{{cite book|last=Willett Cunnington|first=C.|title=The history of underclothes|date=1992|publisher=Dover Pub.|location=New York|isbn=9780486319780|page=291|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PUXDAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT291#v=onepage&q&f=false|author2=Cunnington, Phillis}}</ref>  or first thing in the morning as ideal "for the smart bedroom woman."<ref>{{cite web|title=Boudoir cap, 1926-35|url=http://collections.museumoflondon.org.uk/Online/object.aspx?objectID=object-79650&start=309&rows=1|publisher=Museum of London|accessdate=7 May 2014}}</ref> Towards the end of the 1920s and into the 1930s, the boudoir cap evolved into a form of decorative [[hairnet]].<ref name=cunnington/>

