{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}} {{Use Australian English|date=January 2018}} ''''Mad Monday'''' is a term commonly used in Australia to refer to the traditional end-of-season celebrations for professional players of various codes of [[football]].<ref>{{Cite news | last = Proszenko | first = Adrian | coauthors = | title = Crowe's part in Mad Monday contradicts club stance | work = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | place = Australia | page = | language = | publisher = [[Fairfax Media]] | date = 14 September 2009 | url = http://www.smh.com.au/news/lhqnews/crowes-part-in-mad-monday-contradicts-club-stance/2009/09/13/1252780223370.html | accessdate = 6 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Stevens | first = Mark | coauthors = | title = Jason Akermanis mounts staunch defence of Mad Monday | work = [[Herald Sun]] | place = Australia | page = | language = | publisher = Herald and Weekly Times | date = 2 September 2009 | url = http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/jason-akermanis-mounts-staunch-defence-of-mad-monday/story-e6frf7kx-1225768574251 | accessdate = 6 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Michelle Cazzulino and Stephanie Wilson | first = | coauthors = | title = Mariners' stars blitzkrieged over Mad Monday gag | work = [[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]] | place = Australia | page = | language = | publisher = [[News Limited]] | date = 26 February 2008 | url = http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/mariners-stars-blitzkrieged-over-mad-monday-gag/story-e6frf0a0-1111115645492 | accessdate = 6 November 2010}}</ref> Football matches are typically played on weekends so as the season nears its end with teams being eliminated, by Sunday night all results have been determined and teams will then know if they are to continue in the finals or if their season is over. With the season finished, Mad Monday celebrations ensue, often involving heavy drinking.<ref>{{Cite news | last = [[Craig Bellamy (rugby league)|Bellamy, Craig]] | first = | coauthors = | title = Mad Monday - times have changed | work = [[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]] | place = Australia | page = | language = | publisher = [[News Limited]] | date = 4 September 2008 | url = http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/nrl/mad-monday-times-have-changed/story-e6frext9-1111117385494 | accessdate = 6 November 2010}}</ref> Over the years, Mad Monday celebrations have been the catalyst for image-damaging incidents for professional footballers.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Napier | first = Liam | coauthors = | title = Time for change | work = sportal.com.au | place = Australia | page = | language = | publisher = Sportal | date = 2 November 2010 | url = http://sportal.com.au/league-news-display/time-for-change-101346 | accessdate = 6 November 2010}}</ref> This has led to calls for the tradition to be banned.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Wayne Flower, Antonia Magee and Natalie Tkaczuk Sikora | first = | coauthors = | title = Push to ban 'Mad Monday' | work = [[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]] | place = Australia | page = | language = | publisher = [[News Limited]] | date = 4 September 2008 | url = http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/push-to-ban-mad-monday/story-e6frexni-1111117383509 | accessdate = 6 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Koslowski | first = Michael | coauthors = | title = Field of teams | work = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | place = Australia | page = 6 | language = | publisher = [[Fairfax Media]] | date = 25 September 1997 | url = http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&docID=news970925_0130_8090 | accessdate = 6 February 2011}}</ref>
