{{Quote box |align=right|width=30em|quoted=true |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |salign=center |quote=A Maori legend tells how Ngāhue had a disagreement with his wife, and went forth to seek a new home. The wife, however, caused a green fish named Poutini, a son of the sea god Tangaroa, to pursue her fleeting spouse. Ngahue reached the West Coast of the South Island in line with Aorangi (Mount Cook) with Poutini hot on his tail. Ngahue in his canoe journeyed up the coast, but when off the mouth of the Arahura River, darkness fell. The snow on Mount Tara o Tama mountain at the head of the Arahura River alone furnished brightness. Up the Arahura River sped Ngahue; Poutini followed after, failed to ascend the cascade, was injured, and fell into the deep pool, where the great fish was turned into a greenstone canoe.<ref>{{cite book|title=Lore and history of the South Island Maori|chapter=Te Waipounamu — Westland, the land of the greenstone|page=186|url=http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-TayLore-t1-body1-d22.html|author=W. A. Taylor|publisher=Bascands Limited|location=Christchurch}}</ref>}}

According to [[Maori mythology|Māori mythology]] '''Ngahue''' (sometimes known as '''Ngake''') was a contemporary of [[Kupe]] and one of the first [[Polynesians|Polynesian]] explorers to reach [[New Zealand]]. He was a native of the [[Hawaiki]] and voyaged to New Zealand in “[[Tāwhirirangi]]”, his [[waka (canoe)|waka]] (canoe). No time has been fixed for these voyages, but according to legend he discovered [[pounamu]] (Greenstone) and Ngahue killed a [[Moa]] (large flightless bird - now extinct).<ref>{{cite book|title=The Maori As He Was : A Brief Account of Maori Life as it was in Pre-European Days|chapter=Voyage of Kupe and Ngahue from Eastern Polynesia to New Zealand|page=22|author=[[Elsdon Best]]|location=Wellington|publisher=N.Z.Dominion Museum|year=1934|url=http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-BesMaor-c2-1.html}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Canoe traditions|publisher=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand|date=March 2009|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/canoe-traditions/4/6}}</ref> Pounamu was sometimes called Te Ika-o-Ngāhue (Ngāhue’s fish)<ref>{{cite web|author=Rāwiri Taonui|title=Ngā waewae tapu – Māori exploration - The South Island|publisher=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand|date=March 2009|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/nga-waewae-tapu-maori-exploration/1}}</ref> and they took  several boulders back to Hawaiki.<ref>{{cite web|author=Basil Keane|title=Pounamu – jade or greenstone - Implements and adornment|publisher=Te Ara - the Encyclopedia of New Zealand|date=March 2009|url=http://www.TeAra.govt.nz/en/pounamu-jade-or-greenstone/}}</ref>

