The '''World Cinema Project''' ('''WCP''') is a [[non-profit organization]] devoted to the preservation and restoration of neglected [[world cinema]].
Founded in 2007 as the '''World Cinema Foundation''' by [[Martin Scorsese]], it was inspired by the work of [[The Film Foundation]] in the United States, a similar venture which Scorsese founded with [[George Lucas]], [[Stanley Kubrick]], [[Steven Spielberg]] and [[Clint Eastwood]] in 1990.
The World Cinema Foundation is backed by an advisory board "Filmmaker Council" which includes [[Martin Scorsese]], [[Fatih Akin]], [[Souleymane Cissé]], [[Guillermo Del Toro]], [[Stephen Frears]], [[Alejandro González Iñárritu]], [[Wong Kar-Wai]], [[Abbas Kiarostami]], [[Deepa Mehta]], [[Ermanno Olmi]], [[Raoul Peck]], [[Cristi Puiu]], [[Walter Salles]], [[Abderrahmane Sissako]], [[Elia Suleiman]], [[Bertrand Tavernier]], [[Wim Wenders]], and [[Tian Zhuangzhuang]].<ref>[http://worldcinemafoundation.net/filmmakers-board/ World Cinema Foundation]</ref>
After leaving his position at the [[Film Society of Lincoln Center]], [[Kent Jones (director)|Kent Jones]] became the foundation's executive director.
''Trances'', a music documentary about [[Nass El Ghiwane]] an influential Moroccan music group, was picked by [[Martin Scorsese]] as the inaugural release for the foundation; it was screened at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] in 2007 and at Djemaa el-Fna square in [[Morocco]].<ref>[http://www.film-foundation.org/world-cinema Official Film Foundation site]</ref>
